Looking at the buggy `greatestCommonDivisor` function and the trigger testcases, I need to identify the bug and fix it.

## Analysis

The bug is in line 3-5:
```java
if (Math.abs(u) <= 1 || Math.abs(v) <= 1) {
    return 1;
}
```

This incorrectly returns 1 when either operand has absolute value ≤ 1. The correct behavior should be:
- If `|u| == 1` OR `|v| == 1`, return 1 (they are coprime)
- If `u == 0`, return `|v|`
- If `v == 0`, return `|u|`

The trigger testcases show this bug when reducing fractions like `Fraction.getFraction(0, 100)` which should reduce to `0/1` but the buggy GCD returns 1 for gcd(0, 100), preventing proper reduction.

## Fixed Code

The fix handles the zero cases explicitly and only returns 1 when at least one operand has absolute value exactly equal to 1 (and neither is zero).

## Additional Testcases

I'll create testcases that:
1. Test GCD with one operand being 0 (different from trigger which had 0 in numerator with large denominator)
2. Test edge cases with powers of 2
3. Test cases where both operands are 1 or -1

```json
{
  "fixed_code": [
    "private static int greatestCommonDivisor(int u, int v) {
    // From Commons Math:
    // if either operand is abs 1, return 1:
    if (u == 0) {
        return Math.abs(v);
    }
    if (v == 0) {
        return Math.abs(u);
    }
    if (Math.abs(u) == 1 || Math.abs(v) == 1) {
        return 1;
    }
    // keep u and v negative, as negative integers range down to
    // -2^31, while positive numbers can only be as large as 2^31-1
    // (i.e. we can't necessarily negate a negative number without
    // overflow)
    if (u>0) { u=-u; } // make u negative
    if (v>0) { v=-v; } // make v negative
    // B1. [Find power of 2]
    int k=0;
    while ((u&1)==0 && (v&1)==0 && k<31) { // while u and v are both even...
        u/=2; v/=2; k++; // cast out twos.
    }
    if (k==31) {
        throw new ArithmeticException("overflow: gcd is 2^31");
    }
    // B2. Initialize: u and v have been divided by 2^k and at least
    //     one is odd.
    int t = ((u&1)==1) ? v : -(u/2)/*B3*/;
    // t negative: u was odd, v may be even (t replaces v)
    // t positive: u was even, v is odd (t replaces u)
    do {
        /* assert u<0 && v<0; */
        // B4/B3: cast out twos from t.
        while ((t&1)==0) { // while t is even..
            t/=2; // cast out twos
        }
        // B5 [reset max(u,v)]
        if (t>0) {
            u = -t;
        } else {
            v = t;
        }
        // B6/B3. at this point both u and v should be odd.
        t = (v - u)/2;
        // |u| larger: t positive (replace u)
        // |v| larger: t negative (replace v)
    } while (t!=0);
    return -u*(1<<k); // gcd is u*2^k
}"
